</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="827C4EFA8A5D9D2B0B238BE1356F47D5" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="58C1B4706F143BE08B40D7182EF84687" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C00CEF54B9B69E565B0B00A698991520" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">The species is known from Taiwan and Nepal. It grows on dead wood of angiosperms, with a preference for small branches and twigs.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F20E499F8690AD4CB89F5E66D61690B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="4F89A1A3ECC942864871E1C272DBE88C" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8350D7E7BDB3B447C8C1E50FCE54C687" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
from Latin 
<taxonomicName id="A95BB139F56D6431B7983F94D01EF5C8" lsidName="exilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="exilis">exilis</taxonomicName>
- thin, fine, refers to the small and narrow aculei.
</paragraph>
<caption id="20F5378B04F01799C5F61766A5CEDB44" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<paragraph id="BD13150DD74C71C87E94AA53B8FE2F99" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
